Sass Utility Mixins that encapsulate many common styling patterns. Using them can significantly speed up the styling of a webpage.Here's a quick rundown of what's included in this checkin (@ denotes an import file, + denotes a mixin):nn@ compass/utilitiesn  @ compass/utilities/generaln@ compass/utilities/general/clearfixn  +clearfix - Clearing floats without extra markupn@ compass/utilities/general/tag_cloudn  +tag-cloud(!base_size = 1em) - Emits styles for a tag cloudn  @ compass/utilities/linksn@ compass/utilities/links/hover_linkn  +hover-link - makes a link underlined only when hovered.n@ compass/utilities/links/link_colorsn  +link-colors(!normal, [!hover, !active, !visited, !focus]) - specify all the colorsnof a link with one mixin. Colors not sepecified will not be emitted, this may ornmay not work out depending on how you've defined your style rules.n@ compass/utilities/links/unstyled_linkn  +unstyled-link - A link that looks and acts like the text it is contained withinn  @ compass/utilities/listsn@ compass/utilities/lists/bulletsn  +no-bullet - Turns off the bullet for a single list element.n  +no-bullets - Turns off the bullets for all the list elements in a list.n  +pretty-bullets(!bullet_icon, !width, !height[, !line_height = 18px, !padding = 14px]) - use an icon for the list elements of a list.n@ compass/utilities/lists/horizontal_listn  +horizontal-list - A list where the elements are floated left.n@ compass/utilities/lists/inline_listn  +inline-list - A list where both the list and the list elements are inlined.n  +comma-delimited-list - an inline-list that is comma delimited.n  @ compass/utilities/tablesn@ compass/utilities/tables/alternating_rows_and_columnsn  +alternating-rows-and-columns(!even_row_color, !odd_row_color, !dark_intersection) - The first colors are the even/odd colors respectively and the last argument is a shade that is subtracted from those colors for the even columns.n  @ compass/utilities/textn@ compass/utilities/text/nowrapn  +nowrap - Because remembering whether or not there's a hyphen in white-space is too hardn

Coding spree to clean up the blueprint stylesheets and make them more similar to blueprint-css, more configurable, and more consistent.Breakdown of changes:nn===nnRemove the body scope that is unnecessarily added to many blueprint classes due to the way the mixins were constructed and used. Blueprint mixins that operate on the body tag now follow a pattern where they take the body selector as an argument and must always be mixed into the top level of a stylesheet. The classes will be scoped whenever the selector is not a simple body selector which is the default. Mixins affected: +blueprint-ie, +blueprint-print, +blueprint-typography, and +blueprint-scaffolding. All of these mixins use corresponding +[mixin]-body and +[mixin]-defaults mixins in their implementations that you can use directly if you feel constrained by the requirement to mix into the top-level.nn===nnMade all configurable constants possible to override in a base stylesheet using conditional assignment. Moved many colors that were still hard coded to the colors.sass module so they can be overridden.nn===nnRestored some blueprint defaults even though I didn't like them. With the exception of the blueprint link urls which are now available as a mixin called +blueprint-show-link-urls (they used to just be commented out.)nn===nnGrid constants have been renamed in both the grid and liquid grid modules. These constants are now conditionally assigned to make the grid easily configured.nn===nnThe liquid grid now uses the compass clearfix.nn===nnmoved the primary mixin for a module (where one exists) to the top of the file for clarity of readers.nn===nnblueprint grid classes are now appropriately scoped under the .container class.n

Version is now 0.4.0.This release is a major rewrite of the compass command line utility. Itnis much more flexible and will better support other project types withnvarying project structures.nnThere is a new configuration file format that allows you to specifynthe sass, css, image and javascript locations for your project whennusing compass in a stand-alone (or unsupported project) format.nnCompass frameworks and plugins must now provide a manifest thatnspecifies what files and file types exist in the project template. Thisnpaves the way for other types of templates as the same installationnframework that creates a project can now be used to install othernthings.nnThe compass command line has better help text and more informativenoutput in general.n

Support for Framework Patterns.A pattern is a folder in the framework's templates directory. It mustnhave a manifest file that tells compass what to install and where.nUnlike the project template, a pattern can be stamped out any number ofntimes.nnIt is best for pattern stylesheets to only provide example usage to getnthe user started. All the core styles for the pattern should bendistributed as part of the framework's stylesheets as mixins tonfacilitate easy upgrades and bug fixing on the part of the pattern'snmaintainer.nnPatterns can install stylesheets, images, javascripts, and arbitrarynfiles. The installer will put these assets into the correct locationsnaccording to the project type (E.g. rails, stand-alone).nnExample Usage:ncompass --framework blueprint --pattern buttonsn

Port of the Blueprint Buttons plugin to Compass. This port adds semantic win and color customization to your blueprint button styles. It also let's you choose whether you want to float them right, left, or leave them inline-block.To install this plugin into your project run the following command.ncompass -f blueprint -p buttonsnnOr if you have a rails project:ncompass --rails -f blueprint -p buttonsn

By default, ellipsis text is set tono-wrap. Passnfalse as the first argument if you don't want that.nnNote:nFirefox is the lame browser in this respect, it requires a lot of bendingnover backwards and has many quirky behaviors. Please read the blog post atnhttp://mattsnider.com/css/css-string-truncation-with-ellipsis/ for a fullnexplanation of the issues. Also note that ellipsis text is white-spacensensitive in Firefox, an issue that is sure to affect Haml users more thannmost.n

Refactor of the internal datastructures used to access project configuration. Configuration is now a singly linked list of configuration objects that inherit values and defaults from the next configuration instance. All instances hold a reference to the top of the configuration chain.There is now a consistent API for reading configuration property values:nn<attr>: Reads the fully-resolved attribute after takingnconfiguration inheritance and defaults into account.nraw_<attr>: reads attribute from a configuration object withoutninheritance or defaults.n   default_for(<attr>): reads the default value for an attributendefault_for_<attr>: specifies the default value for an attribute.n<attr>_without_default: reads the inherited attribute without applying defaults.ncomment_for_<attr>: Specifies a comment that will be emitted above thenproperty when serializing the configuration to a file.nnAdditionally, method_missing and respond_to both work down thenconfiguration chain, so any method that is added to a configurationninstance, can be accessed from the top level.nnThe distinction between default and explicitly set values allows compassnto more correctly manage the serialization of attributes when creatingnconfiguration files for projects.nnThe compass configuration can still be accessed vianCompass.configuration, however, the configuration object is no longer ansingleton. This means that you can build several configuration chainsnto track several projects at once. This should ease the use of compassnin other frameworks and plugins that want to use compass internally.n

New framework discovery mechanism: Compass can now load any number of frameworks by passing a directory that contains those frameworks. Each framework can choose to adhere to the naming convention of providing a 'stylesheets' directory and a 'templates' directory, or it can register itself by providing a ruby file at one of the following locations:<plugin>/compass_init.rbn<plugin>/lib/<plugin>.rbn<plugin>/<plugin>.rbnnThe first file found in the above order will be required. The frameworknshould register itself there using the Compass::Frameworks.register method.n

Take margins into account in liquid grid.The previous version of liquid grid would not take margins into propernaccount. With this patch the margins are a correct percentage of thencontainer, and adding multiple margins / columns together should add upnto just about 100% (not entirely accurate, but very close).nnThe math is as follows:nnWith the previous version, you get these numbers:n4.173% grid width * 24 columns = 100.152%, which due to rounding 'fixes'nin the template becomes exactly 100%. However, this is without any margins.nOnce you add margins, you exceed 100%, rendering margins unusable. To addnto the confusion, the margins are not a percentage of the width, but insteadnin 'em' units, making it very difficult to keep the entire grid from gettingnbeyond 100% in width once you add margins.nnWith this patch, you get these numbers:n(3.167% grid width + 1.042% margin) * 24 columns = 101.1016%. Since youndon't use any margin for the last column, you subtract one margin and end upnwith 99.974%. Optimally this number would be 100.000%, but the 0.026% errornis difficult to remove, and an acceptable compromise in my opinion.nnIn summary, this patch enables margins to be used with the liquid grid,nwhich is the expected behaviour.n

In fact, SVG doesn't allow non-opaquencolors at all, so always make the stop-color opaque and set a stop-opacitynattribute where appropriate.  (The spec doesn't say what happens ifncurrentColor is a non-opaque color; caveat user.)n

Add support for positioning sprites with percentagesThe default behaviour for sprites is to position the background imagenwith pixels. This works if the sprite itself will always be displayed innits original pixel dimensions. However, as more and more websites turnnresponsive, is is vital that we can scale images up and down (mostlyndown).nnThis commit will add support for positioning the background image withnpercentages instead of pixels. This will make it easier to scale ansprite image up and down. You won't be able to do it out of the boxnthough, you still need to do some manual work:n  - Using background-size: cover instead of the default (auto)n  - Placing the sprite in a container with a specific width, then usingnthe following magic to the sprite:n  height: 0;n  padding-top: 75%; //image height/width ration  width: 100%;n

Force should be explicitly stated in call.Automatically setting the force flag to true will cause all sprite maps generated by a compiling file to also be regenerated, even if they haven't been changed, in turn causing compilation to be overly slow. This was especially the case in third party programs that watch project directories on their own and call compass compile on individual files (instead of assuming `compass watch`).nnInstead use `compass compile my_file.scss --force`.n
